    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-02-10T09:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-02-10T09:10:00-05:00" n="8"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d8">
                <head>8. Notes of a Telephone Conversation Between Secretary of the Treasury
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP1" type="from">Shultz</persName> and the Under
                    Secretary of the Treasury for Monetary Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_VPA1"
                        type="to">Volcker</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d8fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, RG 56, Office of the Under Secretary of the
                        Treasury, Files of Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_VPA1"
                            >Volcker</persName>, 1969–1974, Accession 56–79–15, Box 1, 1973
                        Devaluation. No classification marking. <persName corresp="#p_SGP1"
                            >Shultz</persName>, who was in Washington, drafted these notes on his
                        conversation with <persName corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName>, who was in
                        Bonn.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1973-02-10T09:10:00-05:00">February 10,
                            1973, 9:10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BW1">Brandt</persName> regards our proposal as serious
                        and deserves to be weighed seriously, but he is unwilling to say he will
                        back it until he had talked with <gloss target="#t_EC1">EC</gloss> partners.
                        He was in touch with them yesterday.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SH1">Schmidt</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName> agreed to <persName
                            corresp="#p_BW1">Brandt</persName>’s doing so, giving <persName
                            corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName> enough time to get to London
                        first.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName> going on to London, then
                        Paris.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName> suggests President to
                                <persName corresp="#p_BW1">Brandt</persName> message:</p>
                        <pb facs="0073" n="42" xml:id="pg_42"/>
                        <p>I am aware of the course of the conversation between Minister <persName
                                corresp="#p_SH1">Schmidt</persName> and Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName>. I know none of the
                            alternatives are free of problems for you or for us. But I firmly
                            believe a constructive solution can be found in the interests of an open
                            world economy with the Federal Republic playing a leading role.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Note danger of <persName corresp="#p_PG2">Pompidou</persName> reaction on
                        Gold.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName> to emphasize usefulness of
                        dropping our capital controls—in terms of doubtful effect and possible
                        impact on inflows.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_VPA1">Volcker</persName> thinks something in
                        neighborhood of 9% is doable in Europe—could mean some alteration of 50–50
                        with Japan, since they are unlikely to go below 260.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
